# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bill-burwell
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bill-burwell/1920-major-league-baseball-season] The **1920 major league baseball season** began on April 14, 1920.
[src:bill-burwell/1920-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 3, with the Brooklyn Robins and Cleveland Indians as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:bill-burwell/1920-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 17th World Series on October 5 and ended with Game 7 on October 12.
[src:bill-burwell/1920-major-league-baseball-season] The Indians defeated the Robins, five games to two, capturing their first championship in franchise history.
[src:bill-burwell/1920-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the Cincinnati Reds from the 1919 season.
[src:bill-burwell/1920-major-league-baseball-season] This was the final season to be presided over by the three-person National Baseball Commission, which ran the major and minor leagues—composed of the American League President, National League President, and one team owner as president.
[src:bill-burwell/1920-major-league-baseball-season] In the wake of the Black Sox scandal, the credibility of baseball had been tarnished with the public and fans and the owners of the teams clamored for credibility to be restored.
[src:bill-burwell/1920-major-league-baseball-season] The owners felt that creating one position with near-unlimited authority was the answer.
[src:bill-burwell/1920-major-league-baseball-season] After the season, the commission was replaced with the newly created office of Commissioner of Baseball.
[src:bill-burwell/1920-major-league-baseball-season] Persisting rumors of the Chicago White Sox throwing the previous year's World Series to the Cincinnati Reds and another game during the 1920 season led to the game's brass looking for ways of dealing with the problems of gambling within the sport.
[src:bill-burwell/1920-major-league-baseball-season] At the time, MLB was governed by a three-man National Baseball Commission composed of American League President Ban Johnson, National League President John Heydler and Cincinnati Reds owner Garry Herrmann.
[src:bill-burwell/1920-major-league-baseball-season] At the request of the other owners, Herrmann left the office reducing the commission to be deadlocked by two.
[src:bill-burwell/1920-major-league-baseball-season] With the owners disliking one or both presidents, calls began for stronger leadership, although they opined they could support the continuation of the leagues' presidencies with a well-qualified Commissioner.
[src:bill-burwell/1920-major-league-baseball-season] A plan that began to circulate and gain support was dubbed the "Lasker Plan", after Albert Lasker, a shareholder of the Chicago Cubs, called for a three-man commission with no financial interest in baseball.
[src:bill-burwell/1920-major-league-baseball-season] With the Black Sox scandal exposed on September 30, 1920, Heydler began calling for the Lasker Plan.
[src:bill-burwell/1920-major-league-baseball-season] All eight NL teams supported the plan, along with three AL teams.
[src:bill-burwell/1920-major-league-baseball-season] The three AL teams were the White Sox, the New York Yankees and the Boston Red Sox.
[src:bill-burwell/1920-major-league-baseball-season] The teams in support of the Lasker Plan wanted federal judge Kenesaw Mountain Landis to take the office of Baseball Commissioner.
[src:bill-burwell/1920-major-league-baseball-season] Johnson, who opposed the plan and thus, the appointment of Landis, had allies in the other five AL clubs, and attempted to get Minor League Baseball to side with him.
[src:bill-burwell/1920-major-league-baseball-season] However, the minor leagues would not, and when the AL teams learned their position, they relented and instead went along with the Lasker Plan.
[src:bill-burwell/1920-major-league-baseball-season] The owners agreed that they needed a person with near-unlimited authority and a powerful person to fill the position of commissioner.
[src:bill-burwell/1920-major-league-baseball-season] The owners approached Landis, who eventually accepted the position as the first Commissioner of Baseball.
[src:bill-burwell/1920-major-league-baseball-season] He drafted the agreement which gave him almost unlimited authority throughout the major and minor leagues – every owner on down to the batboys was accountable to the Commissioner – including barring owners from dismissing him, speaking critically of him in public or challenging him in court.
[src:bill-burwell/1920-major-league-baseball-season] Landis also kept his job as a federal judge.
[src:bill-burwell/1920-major-league-baseball-season] As a result, the owners accepted the terms of the agreement with a scant trace of opposition, if any.
[src:bill-burwell/1920-major-league-baseball-season] The 1920 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:bill-burwell/1920-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 22 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:bill-burwell/1920-major-league-baseball-season] The 154-game format had previously been used since 1904, except for 1919, and would be used until 1961 in the American League and 1962 in the National League.
[src:bill-burwell/1920-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 14 with all but the Washington Senators and Boston Red Sox playing.
[src:bill-burwell/1920-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on October 3, with all teams but the Boston Red Sox and New York Yankees playing.
[src:bill-burwell/1920-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 5 and October 12.
[src:bill-burwell/1920-major-league-baseball-season] The 1920 season featured an extremely rare tripleheader—the third in National League and major-league history, having previously occurred only in 1890 and 1896—when the Pittsburgh Pirates hosted the Cincinnati Reds on October 2 for three games, the day before the final day of the regular season.
[src:bill-burwell/1920-major-league-baseball-season] The Reds won the first two games while the Pirates won the third game, which was called after six innings on account of darkness.
[src:bill-burwell/1920-major-league-baseball-season] After an August 31 game between the Philadelphia Phillies and Chicago Cubs, allegations began to arise that the game was fixed.
[src:bill-burwell/1920-major-league-baseball-season] The state court in Chicago opened a grand jury to investigate gambling within baseball.
[src:bill-burwell/1920-major-league-baseball-season] Gambler Billy Maharg came forward with information that he worked with New York gambler Arnold Rothstein and former boxer Abe Attell to get the White Sox to throw the 1919 World Series.
[src:bill-burwell/1920-major-league-baseball-season] The White Sox again were contending for the American League title and were in a near-dead heat with the Cleveland Indians and New York Yankees.
[src:bill-burwell/1920-major-league-baseball-season] However, on September 28, eight White Sox players were indicted and suspended by owner Charlie Comiskey.
[src:bill-burwell/1920-major-league-baseball-season] The Indians pulled ahead and won the pennant by two games over the White Sox.
[src:bill-burwell/1920-major-league-baseball-season] 6 tie games (3 in AL, 3 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:bill-burwell/1920-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 5 and ended on October 12 with the Cleveland Indians defeating the Brooklyn Robins in the 1920 World Series in seven games.
[src:bill-burwell/1920-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago Cubs' Weeghman Park is renamed to Cubs Park.
[src:bill-burwell/1920-major-league-baseball-season] By 1920, the name of Brush Stadium, home of the New York Giants and New York Yankees, fell into disuse, reverting to the Polo Grounds name.
[src:bill-burwell/1920-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals would play their last game at Cardinal Field on June 6, having played 28 seasons there going back to 1893, and returned to Sportsman's Park on July 1, having previously been their home venue for 11 season from 1882 to 1892, as well as the home of the St.
[src:bill-burwell/1920-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns since their relocation from Milwaukee, Wisconsin in 1902.
[src:bill-burwell/1920-major-league-baseball-season] The Cardinals would go on to play at Sportsman's Park for another 47 seasons through early 1966.
[src:bill-burwell/1921-major-league-baseball-season] The **1921 major league baseball season** began on April 13, 1921.
[src:bill-burwell/1921-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 2, with the New York Giants and New York Yankees as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:bill-burwell/1921-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 18th World Series on October 5 and ended with Game 8 on October 13.
[src:bill-burwell/1921-major-league-baseball-season] In the first Subway Series World Series, the Giants defeated the Yankees, five games to three, capturing their second championship in franchise history, since their previous in 1905.
[src:bill-burwell/1921-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the Cleveland Indians from the 1920 season.
[src:bill-burwell/1921-major-league-baseball-season] 1921 was the first of three straight seasons in which the Yankees would lead the majors in wins.
[src:bill-burwell/1921-major-league-baseball-season] Babe Ruth broke the single season home run record for the third consecutive season by hitting 59 home runs in 152 games.
[src:bill-burwell/1921-major-league-baseball-season] Ruth also broke Roger Connor's record for the most home runs all time when he hit his 139th home run on July 18 against Bert Cole.
[src:bill-burwell/1921-major-league-baseball-season] The record for career strikeouts, previously held by Cy Young was also broken in 1921 by Walter Johnson; Johnson led the league in strikeouts with 143 and ended the season with 2,835 strikeouts.
[src:bill-burwell/1921-major-league-baseball-season] Young struck out 2,803 during his career.
[src:bill-burwell/1921-major-league-baseball-season] The Cincinnati Reds set a Major League record for the fewest strikeouts in a season, with only 308.
[src:bill-burwell/1921-major-league-baseball-season] Future Hall of Famers Kiki Cuyler and Goose Goslin both debuted in September 1921.
[src:bill-burwell/1921-major-league-baseball-season] The 1921 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:bill-burwell/1921-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place since the 1904 season (except for 1919) and would be used until 1961 in the American League and 1962 in the National League.
[src:bill-burwell/1921-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 13 with all but the Chicago White Sox and Detroit Tigers playing.
[src:bill-burwell/1921-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on October 2.
[src:bill-burwell/1921-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 5 and October 13.
[src:bill-burwell/1921-major-league-baseball-season] 3 tie games (2 in AL, 1 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:bill-burwell/1921-major-league-baseball-season] The Philadelphia Athletics had two tie games.
[src:bill-burwell/1921-major-league-baseball-season] The Detroit Tigers and Washington Senators had one tie game each.
[src:bill-burwell/1921-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 5 and ended on October 13 with the New York Giants defeating the New York Yankees in the 1921 World Series in eight games.
[src:bill-burwell/1921-major-league-baseball-season] On August 5, the Pittsburgh Pirates 8–5 victory over the Philadelphia Phillies at Forbes Field was the first Major League game to be broadcast on radio.
[src:bill-burwell/1921-major-league-baseball-season] Harold Arlin calls the game for Pittsburgh station KDKA.
[src:bill-burwell/1928-major-league-baseball-season] The **1928 major league baseball season** began on April 10, 1928.
[src:bill-burwell/1928-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on September 30, with the St.
[src:bill-burwell/1928-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals and New York Yankees as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:bill-burwell/1928-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 25th World Series on October 4 and ended with Game 4 on October 9.
[src:bill-burwell/1928-major-league-baseball-season] In the second iteration of this World Series matchup, the Yankees swept the Cardinals in four games, capturing their third championship in franchise history, and the fifth team to win back-to-back World Series.
[src:bill-burwell/1928-major-league-baseball-season] This was the seventh of eight seasons that "League Awards", a precursor to the Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award (introduced in 1931), were issued.
[src:bill-burwell/1928-major-league-baseball-season] The 1928 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:bill-burwell/1928-major-league-baseball-season] American League Opening Day took place on April 10 with the Boston Red Sox and Washington Senators playing, while National League Opening Day took place the following day.
[src:bill-burwell/1928-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on September 30.
[src:bill-burwell/1928-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 4 and October 9.
[src:bill-burwell/1928-major-league-baseball-season] 4 tie games (2 in AL, 2 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:bill-burwell/1928-major-league-baseball-season] The Boston Red Sox, Chicago White Sox, Cleveland Indians, and Washington Senators had one tie game each.
[src:bill-burwell/1928-major-league-baseball-season] The Cincinnati Reds and New York Giants had one tie game each.
[src:bill-burwell/1928-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 4 and ended on October 9 with the New York Yankees sweeping the St.
[src:bill-burwell/1928-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals in the 1928 World Series in four games.
[src:bill-burwell/1928-major-league-baseball-season] The Cleveland Indians' Dunn Field reverts to the name League Park, following the sale of the team by team owner Jim Dunn.
[src:bill-burwell/1947-major-league-baseball-season] The **1947 major league baseball season** began on April 15, 1947.
[src:bill-burwell/1947-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on September 28, with the Brooklyn Dodgers and New York Yankees as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:bill-burwell/1947-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 44th World Series on September 30 and ended with Game 7 on October 6.
[src:bill-burwell/1947-major-league-baseball-season] In the second iteration of this Subway Series World Series matchup, the Yankees defeated the Dodgers, four games to three, capturing their 11th championship in franchise history, since their previous in 1943.
[src:bill-burwell/1947-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the St.
[src:bill-burwell/1947-major-league-baseball-season] The 14th All-Star Game was held on July 8 at Wrigley Field in Chicago, Illinois, home of the Chicago Cubs.
[src:bill-burwell/1947-major-league-baseball-season] The 1947 season is most notable as the year that the baseball color line broke, thanks to the Brooklyn Dodgers starting Jackie Robinson on Opening Day.
[src:bill-burwell/1947-major-league-baseball-season] On April 15, Opening Day for the National League's Brooklyn Dodgers, Jackie Robinson was in the Dodgers' lineup, playing first base against the Boston Braves at Ebbets Field.
[src:bill-burwell/1947-major-league-baseball-season] His appearance in a major league game broke the baseball color line, the practice of excluding players of black African descent.
[src:bill-burwell/1947-major-league-baseball-season] Though he endured epithets and death threats, as well as a slow start, his skill would earn him the first ever Rookie of the Year award, named in Robinson's honor 40 years later.
[src:bill-burwell/1947-major-league-baseball-season] Halfway through the season on July 5, the American League's Cleveland Indians debuted Larry Doby, becoming the first black player in the American League and breaking the AL color line.
[src:bill-burwell/1947-major-league-baseball-season] Doby was a more low-key figure, suffered many of the same indignities that Robinson did, albeit with less press coverage.
[src:bill-burwell/1947-major-league-baseball-season] Kansas City Monarchs star Willard Brown and teammate Hank Thompson briefly played for the St.
[src:bill-burwell/1947-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns, becoming the third and fourth Black players in either the NL or AL, and made the St.
[src:bill-burwell/1947-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns the first of either the NL or AL to field two Black players on one roster.
[src:bill-burwell/1947-major-league-baseball-season] Brown was the first black player to hit a home run in the American League.
[src:bill-burwell/1947-major-league-baseball-season] The 1947 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:bill-burwell/1947-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 15, featuring all sixteen teams, continuing the trend from 1945.
[src:bill-burwell/1947-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on September 28, which also saw all sixteen teams play, continuing the trend from the previous season.
[src:bill-burwell/1947-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first time since 1940 that all sixteen teams played their first and last games on the same days.
[src:bill-burwell/1947-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between September 30 and October 6.
[src:bill-burwell/1947-major-league-baseball-season] 11 tie games (7 in AL, 4 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:bill-burwell/1947-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on September 30 and ended on October 6 with the New York Yankees defeating the Brooklyn Dodgers in the 1947 World Series in seven games.
[src:bill-burwell/1947-major-league-baseball-season] Previously, the Indians would typically play home games at League Park on weekdays and Cleveland Stadium on weekends.
[src:bill-burwell/1947-major-league-baseball-season] They would go on to play at Cleveland Stadium for a total of 60 seasons through 1993.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-in-baseball-p01] The following are the baseball events of the year 1960 throughout the world.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-pittsburgh-pirates-season-p01] The **1960 Pittsburgh Pirates season** was the team's 79th season.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-pittsburgh-pirates-season-p01] The team finished with a record of 95–59, seven games in front of the second-place Milwaukee Braves to win their first National League championship in 33 seasons.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-pittsburgh-pirates-season-p01] The team went on to play the heavily favored New York Yankees, whom they defeated 4 games to 3 in one of the most storied World Series ever.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-pittsburgh-pirates-season-p01] At the 1959 Winter Meetings, Pirates general manager Joe L.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-pittsburgh-pirates-season-p01] Brown had agreed to trade Dick Groat to the Kansas City Athletics in exchange for Roger Maris.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-pittsburgh-pirates-season-p01] Pirates manager Danny Murtaugh had advised Brown that he did not want to lose Groat, and the deal was never finalized.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-pittsburgh-pirates-season-p01] Maris was eventually traded to the Yankees, and both players would go on to win the MVP for their respective leagues and face each other in the World Series.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-pittsburgh-pirates-season-p01] On September 6, team captain Dick Groat was drilled on his left wrist by an inside pitch from Braves pitcher Lew Burdette.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-pittsburgh-pirates-season-p01] Groat was lost for the rest of the season.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-pittsburgh-pirates-season-p01] Dick Schofield stepped in for the injured Groat and went three for three in that September 6 game.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-pittsburgh-pirates-season-p01] The Pirates won the game 5–3 and Schofield would go on to hit .414 for the rest of the season.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-pittsburgh-pirates-season-p01] On September 25 in Milwaukee, the Pirates clinched their first pennant in 33 years.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-pittsburgh-pirates-season-p01] The 1960 Pirates team, which featured eight All-Stars, was widely predicted to lose the World Series to a powerful New York Yankees team.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-pittsburgh-pirates-season-p01] October 5, 1960, at Forbes Field in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-pittsburgh-pirates-season-p01] October 6, 1960, at Forbes Field in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-pittsburgh-pirates-season-p01] October 8, 1960, at Yankee Stadium in New York City.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-pittsburgh-pirates-season-p01] October 9, 1960, at Yankee Stadium in New York City.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-pittsburgh-pirates-season-p01] October 10, 1960, at Yankee Stadium in New York City.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-pittsburgh-pirates-season-p01] October 12, 1960, at Forbes Field in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-pittsburgh-pirates-season-p01] October 13, 1960, at Forbes Field in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] The **1960 World Series** was the championship series of Major League Baseball's (MLB) 1960 season.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] The 57th edition of the World Series, it was a best-of-seven playoff that matched the National League (NL) champion Pittsburgh Pirates against the American League (AL) champion New York Yankees.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] In Game 7, Bill Mazeroski hit the series winning ninth-inning home run, the first time a winner-take-all World Series game ended with a home run, and the first World Series to end on a home run.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] Mazeroski's home run gave the Pirates their third title overall and their first since 1925.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] Despite losing the series, the Yankees scored 55 runs, the most runs scored by any one team in World Series history, and more than twice as many as the Pirates, who scored 27.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] The Yankees won three blowouts (16–3, 10–0, and 12–0), while the Pirates won four close games (6–4, 3–2, 5–2, and 10–9) to win the series.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] The Pirates' run differential of minus 28 is the lowest ever by any team, winner or loser, in a World Series.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] The Series MVP was Bobby Richardson of the Yankees, the only time in history that the award has been given to a member of the losing team, though the rules were different at this time.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] Votes had to be in by the start of the 8th inning of Game 7, at which point the Yankees were in the lead, and this was the first time since the series MVP award was created in 1955 that the team leading at that point did not go on to win.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] Richardson was also the first non-pitcher to be named MVP.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] This World Series featured seven past, present, or future league Most Valuable Players.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] The Yankees, winners of their 10th pennant in 12 years, outscored the Pirates 55–27 in this Series, out-hit them 91–60, out-batted them .338 to .256, hit 10 home runs to Pittsburgh's four (three of which came in Game 7), got two complete-game shutouts from Whitey Ford—and lost.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] The Pirates' inconsistent pitching and Yankees' manager Casey Stengel's controversial decision not to start Ford in Games 1 and 4 resulted in the peculiar combination of close games and routs.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] Ford (Games 3 and 6) and Vern Law (Games 1 and 4) were excellent, while Pirates relief pitcher Roy Face was a major factor in Games 1, 4 and 5.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] The Yankees also committed twice as many errors as the Pirates in the series.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] The Yankees had 8 errors while the Pirates had four errors.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] The Yankees threw Art Ditmar against the Pirates' Vern Law (the NL Cy Young Award winner) in Game 1.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] In the top of the first inning, New York right fielder Roger Maris, the eventual 1960 AL MVP, drilled a home run off Law to give the Yankees a 1–0 lead.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] In the bottom half, however, the Pirates evened the score when Bill Virdon walked, stole second, advanced to third on an error by shortstop Tony Kubek, and scored on a double by eventual National League Most Valuable Player Dick Groat.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] Bob Skinner then singled to drive in Groat and stole second, coming home on a single by Roberto Clemente.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] This was enough to compel Casey Stengel, the Yankee manager, to pull Ditmar in favor of Jim Coates, who finished the inning.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] In the fourth, New York cut the lead to one run when Maris singled, moved to second on a Mickey Mantle walk, took third on a fly out by Yogi Berra, and scored on a single by Bill Skowron.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] But the Pirates extended their lead to 5–2 in the fourth when Don Hoak walked and Bill Mazeroski homered.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] Game 2, matching New York's Bob Turley against the Pirates' Bob Friend, saw the Yankees pummel Pittsburgh 16–3.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] The game was scoreless until the top of the third, when the Yankees jumped out to a 2–0 lead.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] Second baseman Bobby Richardson walked, was sacrificed over to second by Turley, and scored on a single by Tony Kubek.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] Gil McDougald then doubled, plating Kubek all the way from first base.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] Turley aided his own cause with an RBI single in the fourth, driving home Richardson, who had singled and moved to second on a passed ball.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] Although Hoak doubled home Gino Cimoli in the bottom of the fourth to break the shutout, the Yankees extended their lead to 5–1 courtesy of a two-run home run by Mantle off Fred Green.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] In the sixth, the solid Yankee lead turned into a rout.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] Elston Howard hit a lead-off triple and scored on Bobby Richardson's double to chase Green from the game.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] A passed ball by Smoky Burgess and error by shortstop Dick Groat on Tony Kubek's ground ball put runners on first and third with one out before McDougald's RBI single made it 7–1 Yankees.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] After a walk and strikeout, Yogi Berra's two-run single and Bill Skowron's RBI single made it 10–1 Yankees.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] Red Witt relieved Labine and allowed back-to-back RBI singles to Howard and Richardson that made it 12–1 Yankees.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] Mantle continued the onslaught by blasting a three-run home run in the seventh off Joe Gibbon and scoring on a wild pitch by Tom Cheney in the ninth after walking and moving to third on a double, making it 16–1 Yankees.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] Although the Pirates tacked on two runs in the bottom half of the frame on back-to-back RBI singles by Gino Cimoli and Smoky Burgess, Bobby Shantz relieved Turley and got Don Hoak to hit into the game-ending double play.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] This decisive Yankee victory tied the series at a game apiece.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] For Game 3, the Series shifted to Yankee Stadium as Stengel sent Whitey Ford to the mound against Pittsburgh's Vinegar Bend Mizell.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] Ford had somewhat of an off year (12–9, 3.08 ERA and 192.2 IP) for his lofty standards, but was brilliant against the Pirates.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] The Yankees continued the offensive onslaught they displayed in Game 2, grabbing a 6–0 lead by the end of the first inning.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] After two singles, Bill Skowron drove in the first run with an RBI single.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] After a walk loaded the bases, Elston Howard added another run with an RBI single off Clem Labine before Bobby Richardson capped the scoring with a grand slam (during the regular season, Richardson had hit only one home run, off Baltimore's Arnie Portocarrero on April 30).
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] The next time a first inning World Series Grand slam would be hit would be in the 2021 World Series, 61 years later.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] In the fourth, the Bronx Bombers added on four more runs, courtesy of a two-run home run by Mickey Mantle off Fred Green and—after three singles had loaded the bases—a two-run single by Richardson off Red Witt.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] The Pirates, meanwhile, could not get anything going against Ford, who tossed a masterful four-hitter.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] The Pirates had seen their pitching fail them in the last two games, as the team fell victim to the powerful Yankee bats.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] This was not the case in Game 4, however, as Pittsburgh sent Game 1 winner Vern Law to the hill against Ralph Terry.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] The game was scoreless until the bottom of the fourth, when Bill Skowron launched a home run off Law to give New York a 1–0 advantage.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] The very next half-inning, though, Pittsburgh stormed back, when with two on and two outs, Law doubled in Gino Cimoli to tie the game and Bill Virdon's two-run single put the Pirates up 3–1.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] Law kept the potent pinstripers at bay, though the Yankees did scratch and claw for a single run in the bottom of the seventh when Skowron doubled, moved to third on a single by McDougald, and scored on a fielder's choice on a ball hit by Richardson.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] After a pinch-hit single by Johnny Blanchard, Pirate manager Danny Murtaugh brought in reliever Roy Face, who held the fort for the final 2+2⁄3 innings as Pittsburgh tied the series at two games apiece to ensure a return to Forbes Field.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] As it turned out, on this day Ditmar could not get out of the second inning once again.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] Dick Stuart singled and was forced out at second on a fielder's choice hit by Gino Cimoli, who then moved to third on a double by Smoky Burgess.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] Don Hoak then slapped a ground ball toward Yankee shortstop Tony Kubek, who flipped it to third baseman Gil McDougald in an attempt to retire Burgess, who was attempting to advance.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] However, McDougald dropped the ball for an error (Kubek's toss was accurate), allowing Cimoli to score, with Burgess safe at third, and Hoak reaching second on the error.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] Bill Mazeroski then lashed a double to left, scoring Burgess and Hoak.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] After this offensive outburst, Stengel yanked Ditmar and replaced him with Luis Arroyo, who finally ended the inning and stranded Mazeroski.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] The next half-inning, New York picked up a run when Elston Howard doubled, moved to third on a ground-out by Bobby Richardson, and scored on another grounder by Kubek.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] However, the Pirates extended their lead back to three runs in the third, when Roberto Clemente singled home Groat, who led off with a double.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] In the bottom of the third, Roger Maris touched Haddix for a home run to deep right field.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] Otherwise, however, the Pittsburgh hurler was in fine form, holding the Yankees at bay until the seventh, when he was replaced by Face.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] In the ninth, the Pirates added an insurance run off Ryne Duren.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] Smoky Burgess had singled and taken second on an error; he was replaced at second by pinch-runner Joe Christopher, who moved to third on a wild pitch, and was singled in by Hoak.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] Face then shut down the Yankees once again to give the Pirates a 5–2 victory and 3–2 series lead.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] For the sixth contest in Pittsburgh, the Yankees started Whitey Ford against the Pirates' Bob Friend.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] And as was the case the last time Ford had toed the rubber for the Yanks in Game 3, his teammates relentlessly mashed the ball, en route to a resounding 12–0 victory.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] In the top of the second, the Yankees went to work.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] After a Yogi Berra walk and a Bill Skowron single, Elston Howard was hit by a pitch to load the bases (Eli Grba ran for him).
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] Ford himself then notched the first RBI of the game, with a ground ball single to his counterpart Friend that scored Berra.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] The next inning, after a lead-off hit-by-pitch and double, Mantle cracked a two-run single that scored Tony Kubek and Roger Maris.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] After a Yogi Berra single moved Mantle to third, Pirates skipper Danny Murtaugh removed the clearly ineffective Friend in favor of Tom Cheney.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] Cheney, however, fared no better, as a Bill Skowron sacrifice fly scored Mantle and, after a single, a Richardson triple to deep left field scored Berra and Johnny Blanchard, making the score 6–0.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] The Yankees then ran away with the game, scoring two runs in each of the sixth, seventh, and eighth innings.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] In the sixth, Clete Boyer hit a lead-off triple off Fred Green and scored on Kubek's single.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] After another single, Berra's RBI single off Clem Labine made it 8–0 Yankees.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] Next inning, after a lead-off double by Blanchard, Richardson ripped his second RBI triple of the contest, and Ford added his second RBI courtesy of a fielder's choice on a sacrifice bunt.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] In the eighth, Berra hit an RBI single with a runner on second, and later scored on Blanchard's double.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] As in Game 3, Ford was his masterful self, not letting the Pirates mount anything resembling a rally for the full nine innings.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] His second shutout of the series was critical, as it forced Game 7.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] Yankee manager Casey Stengel would come under fire in Mickey Mantle's autobiography for letting Ford finish this game—instead of removing him once the Yankees had a comfortable lead—thus making him unavailable out of the bullpen if needed in Game 7.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] For the deciding seventh game, Bob Turley, the winning pitcher in Game 2, got the nod for the Yankees against the Pirates' Vern Law, the winning pitcher in Games 1 and 4.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] Turley lasted only one inning plus one batter.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] After retiring the first two batters, Turley walked Bob Skinner, then first baseman Rocky Nelson homered, Pittsburgh's first home run since Bill Mazeroski's in Game 1, to give the Pirates a 2–0 lead.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] Turley was then pulled after giving up a single to Smoky Burgess leading off the second.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] Don Hoak then drew a walk against Bill Stafford, and a bunt single by Mazeroski loaded the bases.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] Stafford appeared to get the Yankees out of trouble after inducing Law to hit into a double play, pitcher to catcher to first.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] But lead-off man Bill Virdon's single to right scored Hoak and Mazeroski and increased the Pirates' lead to 4–0.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] The Yankees got on the board in the fifth on Bill Skowron's lead-off home run, his second of the Series.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] In the sixth, Bobby Richardson led off with a single and Tony Kubek drew a walk.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] Elroy Face relieved Law and got Roger Maris to pop out to Hoak in foul territory, but Mickey Mantle singled to score Richardson.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] Face then blew the save when Yogi Berra followed with a three-run shot to right that gave the Yankees their first lead, 5–4.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] The Yankees extended their lead to 7–4 in the eighth with two more runs off Face.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] With two out, Berra walked, and Skowron singled when the Pirates couldn't get a force-out.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] Johnny Blanchard (who had replaced Elston Howard at catcher for game 7) then singled to score Berra, and Clete Boyer doubled to score Skowron.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] But the Pirates retook the lead with a 5-run eighth inning.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] Gino Cimoli (pinch-hitting for Face) led off with a single, and Virdon hit a ground ball to short for what could have been a double play.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] But the ball instead took a bad hop and hit Kubek in the throat, leaving everybody safe and knocking the wind out of Kubek.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] He eventually got up, and game footage showed him arguing with manager Stengel, seemingly insisting he was ok to stay in the game.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] He was eventually coaxed off the field and replaced.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] He was taken to a hospital and kept overnight for observation due to concerns surrounding his trachea swelling up and thus, causing difficulty breathing.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] Back on the field, Dick Groat then chased Bobby Shantz (who had entered the game in the third and had pitched five innings, having not pitched more than four in any game during the regular season) with a single to score Cimoli and send Virdon to second.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] Jim Coates relieved Shantz and got Skinner out on a sacrifice bunt, which moved the runners up.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] Nelson followed with a fly ball to right, and Virdon declined to challenge Maris' throwing arm.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] The high chopper allowed Virdon to score, cutting the Yankee lead to 7–6.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] Hal Smith, who had replaced Smoky Burgess at catcher after being pinch-run for by Joe Christopher followed with a three-run home run to give the Pirates a 9–7 lead.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] Game 4 loser Ralph Terry relieved Coates and got the last out.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] Bob Friend, an 18-game winner for the Pirates and their starter (and loser) in Games 2 and 6, came on in the ninth to try to protect the lead.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] Bobby Richardson and pinch-hitter Dale Long both greeted him with singles, and Pirates manager Danny Murtaugh was forced to remove the veteran pitcher in favor of Harvey Haddix.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] Although he got Roger Maris to foul out, Haddix gave up a key single to Mickey Mantle that scored Richardson and moved Long to third.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] Yogi Berra followed, hitting a sharp grounder to first, with Rocky Nelson easily getting the second out.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] Had Mantle been out on the play, the run would likely not have counted since the play happened so quickly that the runner on third might not have crossed the plate before the out was recorded.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] With Mantle safe, the inning continued, but ended when Bill Skowron hit into a force play.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] Ralph Terry returned to the mound in the bottom of the ninth.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] The first batter to face him was Bill Mazeroski.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] As the Pirates erupted, the Yankees stood across the field in stunned disbelief.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] The improbable champions were outscored, out-hit, and outplayed, but somehow had managed to pull out a Game 7 victory.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] Years later, Mickey Mantle was quoted in Ken Burns' documentary *Baseball* as saying that losing the 1960 series was the only loss, amateur or professional, he cried actual tears over.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] For Bill Mazeroski, by contrast, his Series-clinching home run was the highlight of a Hall of Fame career otherwise notable mostly for excellent defense.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] Mazeroski became the first player to end the World Series with a home run.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] Thirty-three years later, Joe Carter would become the only other player to end a World Series with a home run, doing so for the Toronto Blue Jays in the 1993 World Series against the Pirates' in-state rivals, the Philadelphia Phillies, albeit in Game 6.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] Because of the game’s back-and-forth nature (especially in the eighth and ninth innings) and historic conclusion, the game is considered by some to be the greatest game in MLB history, as well as one of the greatest games in the history of professional sports.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] Although most noted for the series-ending homer, Game 7 is also the only game in all of postseason history with no strikeouts recorded by either side.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] Bobby Richardson of the Yankees was named MVP of the Series, the only time someone from the losing team has been so honored.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] He batted .367 with 12 RBIs and eight runs in the Series and hit the key grand slam in Game 3.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] Prior to the mid-1970s, television networks and stations generally did not preserve their telecasts of sporting events, choosing instead to tape over them.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] As a result, the broadcasts of the first six games are no longer known to exist.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] The lone exception is a black-and-white kinescope of the entire telecast of Game 7, which was discovered in a wine cellar in Bing Crosby's former home in Hillsborough, California, in December 2009.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] A part-owner of the Pirates who was too superstitious to watch the Series live, Crosby listened to the decisive contest with his wife Kathryn and two friends on a shortwave radio in Paris, France.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] Wanting to watch the game at a later date only if the Pirates won, he arranged for the telecast to be recorded by Ampex, in which he also held a financial investment.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] After viewing the kinescope, he placed it in his wine cellar, where it sat untouched for 49 years.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] It was finally found by Robert Bader, vice-president of marketing and production for Bing Crosby Enterprises, while looking through videotapes of Crosby's television specials which were to be transferred to DVD.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] The five-reel set is the only known complete copy of the historic game, which was originally broadcast in color.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] The NBC television announcers for the Series were Bob Prince and Mel Allen, the primary play-by-play voices for the Pirates and Yankees respectively.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] Prince called the first half of Game 7 and conducted post-game interviews in the Pittsburgh clubhouse, while Allen did the latter portion of the game.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] On October 13, 2010, for the 50th anniversary of the series winning home run, a gala was hosted by the Byham Theater in downtown Pittsburgh, where the historic telecast of Game 7 was re-aired in its entirety.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] Bill Virdon, 1960 MVP Dick Groat and Yankee Bobby Richardson were guest speakers, with actor and Pittsburgh native Jeff Goldblum hosting the event.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] The MLB Network would air the game and gala on December 15, 2010.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] The telecast was also released on DVD by A&E Home Video.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] To date, the Pirates are the only team to win a seven-game postseason series while being out-scored by 28 runs or more.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] This would prove to be Casey Stengel's last World Series, as the Yankees soon sent him into retirement.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] This led to his famous remark, "I'll never make the mistake of turning 70 again." Mazeroski and Clemente were the last two remaining Pirates players from the 1960 World Series winners along with manager Danny Murtaugh and third-base coach Frank Oceak, when the Pirates won the World Series in 1971.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] To date, this is the last championship in any of the four major sports to be won in Pittsburgh by the home team, as the Pirates' two subsequent World Series championships in 1971 and 1979, both against the Baltimore Orioles, were clinched at Memorial Stadium.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] The Pittsburgh Penguins have won all five of their Stanley Cup titles on the road, and the Pittsburgh Steelers have won all six of their Super Bowl championships at neutral sites, as is customary in the NFL.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] The Yankees returned to the World Series the following year and the year after, and won back-to-back championships over the Cincinnati Reds and San Francisco Giants in five and seven games respectively.
[src:bill-burwell/1960-world-series] In 2025, the NBC radio broadcast of Game 7 by Chuck Thompson was selected by the Library of Congress for preservation in the National Recording Registry.
[src:bill-burwell/bill-burwell] In 1917, Burwell was drafted into the United States Army.
[src:bill-burwell/bill-burwell] During the Battle of Saint-Mihiel in 1918, Burwell volunteered for the dangerous mission of attacking German machine gun nests, and his pitching hand was injured by a bullet.
[src:bill-burwell/bill-burwell] One of his fingers was shattered and the tip of the finger was lost, causing his fingers to have a slight curl.
[src:bill-burwell/bill-burwell] He'd discover after his hand healed that he could throw a sinker.
[src:bill-burwell/bill-burwell] He pitched for all or parts of 12 straight seasons, between 1923 and 1934, for the Indianapolis Indians of the American Association.
[src:bill-burwell/bill-burwell] In Major League Baseball, he appeared in 66 career games for the 1920–21 St.
[src:bill-burwell/bill-burwell] Louis Browns and four contests for the 1928 Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:bill-burwell/bill-burwell] In his 70 MLB games, six as a starting pitcher, he won nine games and lost eight, with a 4.37 earned run average.
[src:bill-burwell/bill-burwell] He posted six saves and one complete game, allowing 253 hits and 79 bases on balls, with 49 strikeouts, in 2181⁄3 innings pitched.
[src:bill-burwell/bill-burwell] He also fashioned a lengthy post-pitching career as a minor league manager (including two seasons, 1945–46, as skipper of the Indianapolis franchise) and Major League coach.
[src:bill-burwell/bill-burwell] He worked in the latter role for the Boston Red Sox (1944) and Pittsburgh Pirates (1947–48; 1958–62).
[src:bill-burwell/bill-burwell] While serving as pitching coach on Danny Murtaugh's staff, Burwell was a member of the Pirates' 1960 world championship team.
[src:bill-burwell/bill-burwell] Burwell was acting manager of the Pirates for the final game of the 1947 season, after player-manager Billy Herman resigned with one game remaining.
[src:bill-burwell/bill-burwell] Under Burwell, the Pirates defeated the Cincinnati Reds, 7–0.
[src:bill-burwell/bill-burwell] He also was a longtime scout and roving minor league coach for the Pirates.
[src:bill-burwell/bill-burwell] While working as pitching instructor in the Pirate organization in 1949, Burwell was instrumental to the development of pitcher Vern Law, then toiling for the Class B Davenport Pirates of the Illinois–Indiana–Iowa League.
[src:bill-burwell/bill-burwell] Burwell taught the 19-year-old Law how to change speeds and throw the change-up.
[src:bill-burwell/bill-burwell] Law — winner of the 1960 Cy Young Award as the top pitcher in the majors — later cited Burwell as the coach who most helped him during his time in the minor leagues.
[src:bill-burwell/bill-burwell] Burwell died at age 78 in Ormond Beach, Florida, and is buried in nearby Daytona Beach.
